    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title">&#x201C;Title of Work&#x201D;</head>
                <!--An apparatus may contain all or only some of the following sections.-->
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section">Title</head>
                    <p>Title written “TRAFALGAR” in MSS IA and V.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p>MSS IA, V, [VI]. 
                        Presentation copy in MS IA probably dated February 8 (see part 1, MS IA, “Content,” e). 
                        According to the index of MS VI, the section of the manuscript now torn away contained “Trafalgar,” 
                        probably its rough draft, between "Vesuvius" and "Death."</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p>February 8 and 12. Copy in MS V dated February 12 by Ruskin, with the addition by John James, “Age 11 years”;</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head type="section">Composition &#x0026; Publication</head>
                    <p>Printed PJR, 1:35-37; Works, 2:279-81.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DISCUSSION">
                    <head type="section">Discussion</head>
                    <p>Two patriotic images related to <placeName corresp="#TRAFALGAR">Trafalgar</placeName> hung in the dining room of <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s paternal grandparents, when they lived 
                        in <placeName type="building" corresp="#STJAMESSQEDINBURGH">St. James Square</placeName> in <placeName type="building" corresp="#NEWTOWNEDINBURGH">New Town</placeName> of <placeName corresp="#EDINBURGH">Edinburgh</placeName>. 
                        One was a picture of <persName corresp="#DUFF">Captain George Duff</persName>, killed at <placeName corresp="#TRAFALGAR">Trafalgar</placeName> in <date when="1805">1805</date>, which 
                        <persName corresp="#VAB">Van Akin Burd</persName> suggests may have been an engraving by <persName corresp="#DAWE">George Dawe</persName> after a portrait by <persName corresp="#SHR">Henry Raeburn</persName>. 
                        Two other pictures depicted <persName corresp="#HNVN">Nelson</persName> (<title type="letter" corresp="ctwr_to_jjr_1807-11-02"><persName corresp="#CTWR">Catherine Ruskin</persName> to <persName corresp="#JJR">John James Ruskin</persName>, <date when="1807-11-02">2 November 1807</date></title>, 
                        in <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName> ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title></ref>, 1:12, 14 n. 3).</p>
                </div>
            </div>
